        <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Guidelines for ensuring Status Indicators are accessible to all users and assistive technologies.</p>

        <div class="doc-section">
          <h3 id="accessibility-guidelines" class="doc-h3">Accessibility Guidelines</h3>
          <table class="size-table">
            <thead><tr><th>Guideline</th><th>Requirement</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Label</strong></td><td>Always show text label</td><td>Always show text label for screen readers. If the label is visually hidden, use <code>aria-label</code> or <code>sr-only</code> class.</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Contrast</strong></td><td>WCAG AA compliant</td><td>All dot colors meet WCAG AA contrast requirements against white backgrounds.</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Color Independence</strong></td><td>Text label required</td><td>Text label communicates meaning -- the dot color is supplementary, not the sole indicator.</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Screen Reader</strong></td><td>Announced as label text</td><td>The status is announced as its label text (e.g., "Online", "Offline"). Add <code>role="status"</code> for live updates.</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Keyboard</strong></td><td>Focusable if interactive</td><td>If the Status Indicator is interactive, it must be focusable via Tab with a visible focus ring.</td></tr>
